        "Revenue rose because passenger demand kept recovering: rail and leisure travel rebounded, inbound tourists returned in force, and hotels and real estate were strong. So the top line clearly grew. The reason profit nonetheless slipped is two-fold: costs were higher across the group, and — as with several peers — the prior year had included property-sale gains that did not repeat, making the year-on-year profit comparison harder. So this was not a weakening business so much as rising costs plus a tough comparison eating into a growing top line. In short: more revenue came in, but it cost more to earn and last year's one-off property gains were missing, so profit edged down.",
