        "Record revenue (+3.6%) and profit came from raising the price of each move — higher unit prices — which offset two headwinds at once: a structurally shrinking moving market (Japan's population is aging and people move less) and labor-cost inflation (movers are hard to hire and wages are rising). So Sakai is defending profitability not by doing more moves but by charging more per move and managing costs tightly. The dividend was sharply raised to ¥97 from ¥53, signaling confidence and a stronger shareholder-return stance. In short: pricing discipline beat a shrinking market and rising wages to deliver a record, with a big dividend hike on top.",
